    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1938-10-12T01:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1938-10-12T01:00:00-05:00" n="301"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d301">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">793.94/14048: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Japan</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Grew</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Tokyo</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1938-10-12T15:00:00+09:00"
                            >October 12, 1938—3 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received October 12—8:20 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>660. Our 657, October 12, 10 a.m.<note n="33" xml:id="d301fn33">
                        <ref target="frus1931-41v01#pg_476">
                            <hi rend="italic">Foreign Relations</hi>, Japan, 1931–1941, vol. <hi
                                rend="smallcaps">i</hi>, p. 476</ref>.</note>
                </p>
                <list>
                    <label>1.</label>
                    <item>My British colleague understands that all preparations for landing
                        Japanese forces on the coast of Kwangtung Province for a drive on Canton
                        have been made for some time past and that the Japanese were only awaiting
                        certain circumstances to put the plan into execution. He believes that the
                        circumstances which have brought matters to a head are: (<hi rend="italic"
                            >a</hi>) information that Chiang Kai Shek when he leaves Hankow may
                        proceed to the south instead of to the west, and (<hi rend="italic">b</hi>)
                        a desire to distract public attention in Japan from the delays and
                        occasional defeats incidental to the drive on Hankow, or both.</item>
                    <label>2.</label>
                    <item>Craigie yesterday told the Vice Minister that a drive on Canton could have
                        a seriously adverse effect on Anglo-Japanese relations from <pb facs="0320"
                            n="316" xml:id="pg_316"/> the following points of view: (<hi
                            rend="italic">a</hi>) the danger to Japanese residents in Hong Kong from
                        an enflamed Chinese populace; (<hi rend="italic">b</hi>) the serious problem
                        of Chinese refugees flocking into the colony; (<hi rend="italic">c</hi>) the
                        attendant problem of food supplies; and (<hi rend="italic">d</hi>) the risk
                        of incidents involving British shipping. The Vice Minister merely replied
                        that such of these points as concerned the Japanese authorities on the spot
                        would be referred to them for consideration.</item>
                </list>
                <p>Repeated to Hong Kong for Chungking.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Grew</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
